00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:52.410
to somehow be involved in something

00:11:52.410 --> 00:11:54.790
that stops your daughter
from coming of age.

00:11:54.790 --> 00:11:57.010
You know, she doesn't
get her period.

00:11:57.010 --> 00:11:59.000
Most gymnasts don't
get their period --

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.010
sorry for talking about
periods on a Saturday afternoon.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:04.070
But they don't hit their periods
till their 20's, you know?

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:08.430
Like everything is stopped and
their body develops differently

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:09.730
to accommodate it.

00:12:09.730 --> 00:12:12.290
And they don't want to get breasts

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:15.920
because it will affect
the physics of gymnastics.

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:22.320
So that just like for a writer,
of course that's so exciting.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:25.200
For a person it's tragic.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.390
[ Laughter ]

00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:28.690
Yeah, yeah.

00:12:28.690 --> 00:12:30.940
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair:
And why crime fiction?

00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:34.000
Why do you think you are so
drawn to writing crime novels?

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.260
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Yeah,
I think of that a lot.

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:40.180
I mean, you know, some crime
writers are very much interested

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:43.100
in the procedural elements,
which I am as a reader,

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:44.580
but not as a reader
but not as a writer.

00:12:44.580 --> 00:12:47.010
Because my mind doesn't work.

00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:49.910
My books don't have
like a series of clues.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:51.280
I mean, there are clues sort of,

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:55.760
but it's not like the Agatha
Christie you know, or Nancy Drew

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:58.300
or any of the sort of classic ones.

00:12:58.300 --> 00:13:01.320
But I do like sort
of people in crisis,

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:03.820
how they handle it
and how they respond.

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:07.070
And people kind of reckoning
with their own darkness,

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:09.860
or the darkness of those they love.

00:13:09.860 --> 00:13:13.100
That just endlessly fascinates me.

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:15.820
So I was really the kid who --

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:19.730
and so many crime novelists I
know have had the same experience.

00:13:19.730 --> 00:13:22.630
But you know, you'd be in the
used book store and you're

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:25.340
like ten years old and
there's Helter-Skelter

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:28.860 position:56%
and you open the new one and look
at the pictures, which is grotesque.

00:13:28.860 --> 00:13:30.240
But you do.

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:34.000 position:56%
There's a curiosity that you have
to get comfortable with it yourself.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.270
And also know what
its limits are too.

00:13:37.270 --> 00:13:42.670
So it doesn't become
indulgent or sensational.

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:43.970
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Yeah.

00:13:43.970 --> 00:13:47.310
And then with your process, do
you come up with the crime first

00:13:47.310 --> 00:13:50.160
and then build the world and
the characters around it?

00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:51.900
Or what's your --

00:13:51.900 --> 00:13:55.300
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: It's usually the
character first and situation.

00:13:55.300 --> 00:13:59.750
Sometimes I have a crime and then
I'm trying to find the character.

00:13:59.750 --> 00:14:05.910
I'm trying to matchmake, and it
doesn't -- that's a little harder.

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:09.600
Almost always it's have a
character and then I'm sort

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:10.900
of searching for a crime.

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:13.050
And it's also a real-life
case, like The Fever

00:14:13.050 --> 00:14:18.260
or in this case it wasn't a crime,
but a real-life inspiration.

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.830
But I start with character.

00:14:20.830 --> 00:14:22.950
If I can't nail the
voice of the character,

00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:25.070
then it's the wrong story.

00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:26.370
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Yeah.

00:14:26.370 --> 00:14:27.670
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: So
that has to be --

00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:30.220
you know, I've had
many false starts.

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:32.000
You know, every book
there's been two

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.190
or three false starts
before I find the one.

00:14:34.190 --> 00:14:35.490
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Yeah.

00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:38.620
I don't know how many
people know about The Fever,

00:14:38.620 --> 00:14:40.970
that it really was
drawn from a true story.

00:14:40.970 --> 00:14:43.120
If you want to talk
about that a little bit.

00:14:43.120 --> 00:14:44.420
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Yes, yes.

00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:46.270
Some of you may remember it, but
there was this famous case --

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:49.230
I think it was about
five years ago now.

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:52.190
In upstate New York
these young girls,

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:55.680
all of them developed these
ticks, these motor ticks.

00:14:55.680 --> 00:15:00.910
And it sort of spread through the
school in this very small town.

00:15:00.910 --> 00:15:04.000
And it became sort of a phenomenon.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.020
And Aaron Brockavic arrived.

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:07.380
They thought maybe
it was environmental.

00:15:07.380 --> 00:15:12.190
Other people thought there
was some kind of Lyme disease.

00:15:12.190 --> 00:15:15.150
There were all these
theories about it.

00:15:15.150 --> 00:15:18.180
And in the end it was
primarily diagnosed

00:15:18.180 --> 00:15:23.340
as this psychogenic illness,
this kind of hysteria.

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:27.470
So the symptoms were real, but it
came from a psychological place.

00:15:27.470 --> 00:15:30.870
So that just -- I mean
that just felt

00:15:30.870 --> 00:15:32.470
like it was right in my wheelhouse.

00:15:32.470 --> 00:15:34.780
It was calling to me,
"Write about me."

00:15:34.780 --> 00:15:36.080
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Yeah.

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:37.510
I mean, maybe it was planned,

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:41.670
because it was a Megan Abbott
novel in the making for sure.

00:15:41.670 --> 00:15:45.400
For sure. Tell me a little bit more
about your process and your day.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:46.700
When do you write?

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:49.310
What's the best time of
day for you to write?

00:15:49.310 --> 00:15:50.610
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Yeah.

00:15:50.610 --> 00:15:53.510 position:56%
I have to sort of block out the day.

00:15:53.510 --> 00:15:58.530
So I tend to be most productive in
the morning, but I don't just sit

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:00.520
down and do my two hours.

00:16:00.520 --> 00:16:04.590
I'm not fast enough or
organized, a thinker enough.

00:16:04.590 --> 00:16:09.660
So I just basically write on and
off all day in these sort of spurts

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:11.900
between you know, the distraction.

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:15.560
I mean now, the last eight
months or so there have been

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:17.860 position:56%
so many distractions with the world.

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:21.540
You know, I talked to so
many writers across genre

00:16:21.540 --> 00:16:24.340
that the distraction
of the news has been --

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:28.340
and sort of the need to follow
the news has made it harder.

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:30.200
But I do try to block that out.

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:31.720
And I have these spurts.

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:35.090
In the last few years
I've done some TV writing.

00:16:35.090 --> 00:16:37.870
And that's a different motor.

00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:41.840
Like I can turn that on
at any time and plug in.

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:45.720
It's much faster, because
it's not as interior.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:50.040 position:56%
So I'm really aware of how important
the novel writing process is for me,

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:52.890
that I don't sort of just plug in.

00:16:52.890 --> 00:16:57.810
That I really like try to sit in
that world, imagine the characters

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:00.380
and just sort of --
it's sort of like going

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:03.390
into cold water stage
by stage by stage.

00:17:03.390 --> 00:17:04.710
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Yeah.

00:17:04.710 --> 00:17:10.540
I heard you say once that you
can't sort of have lunch and sort

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:12.850
of pull yourself away
from the atmosphere,

00:17:12.850 --> 00:17:15.240
because then you're
completely derailed.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:16.540
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: It's true.

00:17:16.540 --> 00:17:18.690
People get annoyed and they
think I'm being suppressive.

00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:20.360
Like, "Let's have lunch."

00:17:20.360 --> 00:17:22.010
And I say, "Can we
have dinner instead?"

00:17:22.010 --> 00:17:25.920
You know, because if we have
lunch, then I will sit at lunch

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:30.310 position:56%
and I will probably order a beer,
something I never would normally do,

00:17:30.310 --> 00:17:32.940
because I know I don't
have to go back to work now

00:17:32.940 --> 00:17:34.900
and I have the rest of the day off.

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:36.720
I can't get in that head again,

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:39.970
because I'm in this
social head, you know?

00:17:39.970 --> 00:17:42.620
And it's impossible to get back in.

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:43.920
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Yeah.

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:47.680
Are there real stories going
on in the world right now

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:51.430
that you're watching and
thinking, "That's my next novel"?

00:17:51.430 --> 00:17:52.730
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Yeah.

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:54.030
I have a few on my ticker now.

00:17:54.030 --> 00:17:55.550
I'm sort of following them.

00:17:55.550 --> 00:17:59.770
People now send me them all
the time, which is great.

00:17:59.770 --> 00:18:01.780
There was -- I shouldn't
even say it,

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:03.130
because maybe I'll write about it.

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:07.110
But there was this great case last
year of these twin yoga teachers

00:18:07.110 --> 00:18:10.920
and one of them killed the
other one on a Hawaiian cliff.

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:12.640
She drove the car off a cliff.

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:15.890
And then it turned out they had
this very weird relationship.

00:18:15.890 --> 00:18:18.470
And it's fascinating.

00:18:18.470 --> 00:18:23.090
And I think 30 or 40 people sent
me that article when it came out.

00:18:23.090 --> 00:18:24.970
[Laughs]. "You've got
to write about this."

00:18:24.970 --> 00:18:28.390
Or the teenage girl who
texted her boyfriend

00:18:28.390 --> 00:18:30.760
and then he killed himself,
which is a terrible store.

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:32.970
And actually I wouldn't
write about that.

00:18:32.970 --> 00:18:34.540
You know, you make these decisions.

00:18:34.540 --> 00:18:43.480
That one felt very upsetting to
me and I didn't want to write it.

00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:46.800
But a lot of people
sent me that too.

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:51.270
So in fact, another writer I know
actually emailed me yesterday

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:54.090
to say, "Are you going
to write about it?

00:18:54.090 --> 00:18:55.390
Because I might."

00:18:55.390 --> 00:18:56.690
That's a no-go.

00:18:56.690 --> 00:18:57.990
[Laughs].

00:18:57.990 --> 00:18:59.290
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: Just
don't make it a hit.

00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:00.590
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: That's right.

00:19:00.590 --> 00:19:01.890
And I wouldn't -- you know,
these decisions we make about --

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:03.190
because you live when
you write a novel.

00:19:03.190 --> 00:19:04.490
It takes me a year and a half maybe

00:19:04.490 --> 00:19:05.790
to write a novel, sometimes
a little more.

00:19:05.790 --> 00:19:08.250
And so you're living in
this space for a while.

00:19:08.250 --> 00:19:10.830
And there are certain spaces that
I just know I don't want to live

00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:12.370
in for that long, you know.

00:19:12.370 --> 00:19:14.150
It's too unpleasant.

00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:19.950
I don't have any copilots that feel
right, like with You Will Know Me,

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:21.250
there were characters I liked.

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:23.450
And I knew I would be
comfortable with them.

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:24.750
I like Katie.

00:19:24.750 --> 00:19:28.660
Once I figured out how I liked
her, I could go with her.

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:29.960
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair:
Tell us about Katie.

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:33.300
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Katie, she's -- I
was really resistant to doing kind

00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:35.900
of a classic stage mom,
even though in some ways

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:39.040
from the outside she could
be viewed as a stage mom.

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:45.860 position:56%
So I really wanted her to be someone
who had no plan for her daughter

00:19:45.860 --> 00:19:47.530
to be anything but her daughter.

00:19:47.530 --> 00:19:50.370
But her daughter had
this special talent.

00:19:50.370 --> 00:19:51.670
And early on in the book --

00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:53.990
very early so it's not a spoiler
-- but I won't go into it.

00:19:53.990 --> 00:19:56.570
There's something that happens
to Devin when she's a little girl

00:19:56.570 --> 00:20:01.570
that increases Katie's worry for
her and protectiveness of her.

00:20:01.570 --> 00:20:04.870
And her wanting to make
everything right for her.

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:09.190
And so I think she really thinks
she's doing the right thing

00:20:09.190 --> 00:20:10.490
by Devin.

00:20:10.490 --> 00:20:11.790
In many ways she is.

00:20:11.790 --> 00:20:13.380
But I think it also can be, when
you're in these communities,

00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:16.740
these sports communities
or music communities

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:19.620
or whatever the special
talent is, can be really hard

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:23.790 position:56%
to keep perspective because everyone
you know is also in that world.

00:20:23.790 --> 00:20:26.850 position:56%
And you have no barometer -- you
know, you have no way to measure it.

00:20:26.850 --> 00:20:31.080
And I think that Katie does
get a little lost in that.

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:35.110
But I wanted it to feel that
she was coming from a good space

00:20:35.110 --> 00:20:37.250
so that we would follow her there.

00:20:37.250 --> 00:20:38.800
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: I
love when the mothers say

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:41.040
to her, "What's your secret?

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:43.430
You know, what are
you guys feeding her?

00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:47.300
I'll feed my daughter so
she'll be just as successful.

00:20:47.300 --> 00:20:51.810
Yeah, I do think there's
some of that that goes on.

00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:56.970
The parents are thinking all they
have to do is tweak the appetite

00:20:56.970 --> 00:21:00.660
or the schedule, and it's
really hard on kids I think.

00:21:00.660 --> 00:21:01.960
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: I think so too.

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:04.190
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: The
parents' expectations can be very

00:21:04.190 --> 00:21:06.540
debilitating for the kids.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:07.840
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Oh, so true.

00:21:07.840 --> 00:21:09.140
You know, it's almost
like they're talking

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:11.240 position:56%
about a horserace when they do that.

00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:12.540
What's the diet?

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:14.690
You know, this is our show horse.

00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:15.990
We're competing.

00:21:15.990 --> 00:21:20.100
But there's another part of
it that a lot of prodigies

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:22.220
or just very talented
young athletes,

00:21:22.220 --> 00:21:24.190
they do want it very badly.

00:21:24.190 --> 00:21:27.050
And I think it's very
hard to tell them apart.

00:21:27.050 --> 00:21:28.530
And sometimes they
want it very badly.

00:21:28.530 --> 00:21:32.380
My brother was a very intense
baseball player as a kid.

00:21:32.380 --> 00:21:34.420
And my parents were very involved.

00:21:34.420 --> 00:21:37.310 position:56%
And we went to all the Little League
games and I was the kid sitting

00:21:37.310 --> 00:21:41.570 position:56%
in the stands bored to tears because
the games would last forever.

00:21:41.570 --> 00:21:44.130
And my parents were
really motivated.

00:21:44.130 --> 00:21:46.780
And at a certain point he
lost interest, you know?

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:49.050
He was 14.

00:21:49.050 --> 00:21:52.770
Other things started to
seem interesting to him.

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:58.840 position:56%
But luckily he felt comfortable
saying it and they felt fine I think

00:21:58.840 --> 00:22:03.630
with not surrendering
yourself to baseball anymore.

00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:04.930
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: So you're Drew?

00:22:04.930 --> 00:22:06.230
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: I'm Drew.

00:22:06.230 --> 00:22:07.640
There's a little brother.

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:09.560
I am definitely Drew.

00:22:09.560 --> 00:22:12.470
Yes. I was the bookish one.

00:22:12.470 --> 00:22:15.860
My brother is really bookish too,
but he was a really good athlete

00:22:15.860 --> 00:22:18.610
and I was never -- as stated,
I was never the athlete.

00:22:18.610 --> 00:22:19.910
I wanted to be.

00:22:19.910 --> 00:22:25.770
So I did see it from the outside
so I had a little more perspective.

00:22:25.770 --> 00:22:28.800
The little brother in the book I
think is the only one in the family

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:34.790 position:56%
who really kind of sees what's going
on, even though he's quite young.

00:22:34.790 --> 00:22:36.850
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Blair: I also
noticed that technology --

00:22:36.850 --> 00:22:40.940
social media, which has so
revolutionized what it's

00:22:40.940 --> 00:22:43.590
like to be a teenager right now.

00:22:43.590 --> 00:22:47.230
You don't engage in that a lot.

00:22:47.230 --> 00:22:50.620
And I'm wondering if as a
writer, if you grapple with that,

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:53.230
given that teenagers are
who you really like to --

00:22:53.230 --> 00:22:54.530
&gt;&gt; Megan Abbott: Yes.

00:22:54.530 --> 00:22:55.830
I think about that a lot.

00:22:55.830 --> 00:22:58.010
It's sort of I got a
free pass with this

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:02.960
because Devin doesn't really have
friendships because she's so --

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:05.940
she doesn't have many
peer relationships.

00:23:05.940 --> 00:23:08.560
So that's not part
of her experience.

00:23:08.560 --> 00:23:10.210
It's somewhat a part of The Fever.

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:12.280
But the book I wrote
before that, Dare Me,

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:14.870
which is about the
cheerleading squad --

00:23:14.870 --> 00:23:17.670
if I wrote that now --
that came out in 2012.

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:19.890
There's some texting
and social media in it.

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:24.250
But if I wrote it now, I would have
to write it completely differently.

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:29.490
Because it's become you know
-- so when I wrote it was 2010.

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:33.140
So in the past eight years --
you know, every seven years --

00:23:33.140 --> 00:23:35.550
it's become so much
a function of it.

00:23:35.550 --> 00:23:40.600
But there is something deadly about
reading text messages in a novel.

00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:44.380
You know? Because if your text
messages are anything like mine,

00:23:44.380 --> 00:23:46.120
they are not very literary.

00:23:46.120 --> 00:23:49.930
And they are filled
with emojis and things

00:23:49.930 --> 00:23:53.600
that you know -- that's
not why we read.

00:23:53.600 --> 00:23:54.900
On the other hand,

00:23:54.900 --> 00:23:59.430
if used effectively I
think they can be a tool,

00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:02.660
the way we're so attached
to our phone now.

00:24:02.660 --> 00:24:04.390
